AGI -&nbsp;Paris will dedicate a pedestrian bridge in the city center to the icon of rock Jim&nbsp;Morrison, protagonist of the psychedelic music scene of the 1960s. The tomb of the frontman of the Doors, inside the cemetery of Père-Lachaise, is already a magnet for the nostalgic fans of rock, which every day pay homage in such a number that the cemetery had to erect some barriers around the last remembered dwelling of the American singer.&nbsp;- that moved to the French capital a few months before he died, in July 1971 --fe
&nbsp;
The catwalk crosses the Arsenal, a basin near the Bastille in the center of the capital, a few steps from the bohemian quarter of the Marais, in which&nbsp;Morrison&nbsp; lived the last days. The Doors, founded in Los Angeles in 1965, were among the most influential rock bands of the late 1960s and early 1970s and a pillar of the counterculture of the era. > Among the main successes, "Riders on the Storm", "Light My Fire" and "The End", a song that appears in the 1979 film of Francis Ford Coppola, 'Apocalypse Now'. The charisma of&nbsp;Morrison&nbsp; and its magnetic theatrical interpretations made it a sex symbol, as well as provocative behavior and substance abuse.
&nbsp;
The exact circumstances of the death of&nbsp;Morrison&nbsp; at the age of 27 they are still wrapped in mystery. > The most accredited thesis is that he died by cardiac arrest in his bathtub. However, a French journalist, Sam Bernett, stated in a 2007 book that friends and family modified the official version of the death of&nbsp;Morrison&nbsp; to rehabilitate his reputation. According to Bernett,&nbsp;Morrison died of a heroin overdose in the bathroom of a nightclub, the "Rock 'n' Roll Circus", on the Rive Gauche in Paris.&nbsp;

