AGI - US President Donald Trump insisted that&nbsp;Hamas&nbsp; must release all hostages by February 15 at noon and said that his threat of triggering "hell" on them was the reason why the releases were resumed as part of the ceasefire agreement. "I said at 12 o'clock on Saturday, and suddenly two days ago they said: We'll release the hostages again. But all this started because they said they would not release more hostages and yesterday they said they would. I think they should release them all," he said.
&nbsp;
On Tuesday Trump threatened to unleash "hell" against&nbsp;Hamas&nbsp; if the release of the hostages provided by the peace agreement mediated by the United States, Qatar and Egypt in January in exchange for the release of Palestinian prisoners. Trump added that "all" hostages should be released, which he reiterated today, without clarifying what would have been the consequences of such observance.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
Hamas&nbsp; he announced that he intends to release the Russian-Israeli Sasha (Alexander) Trufanov, Sagui Dekel-Chen, Israeli-American citizen, and the Israeli hostage of Argentine origin Iair Horn. > Israel, on its part, threatened to resume the war in Gaza se&nbsp;Hamas&nbsp; will not release the hostages Saturday, without clarifying how many, taking advantage of Trump's message. "I saw the girls who were treated very badly. You don't know what happened to them, but I do. They were treated very badly, but the ones that will come after will look much worse. I think the most sane minds are taking command first," Trump said, who repeated several times that&nbsp;Hamas&nbsp; had changed his mind thanks to his warning on Tuesday.&nbsp;

