<h2>Vance, no to fire walls or is no longer democracy</h2>
In democracy "there is no room for fire walls" that exclude some parties from power, otherwise it is no longer democracy, the US Vice-President declared, in a clear reference to the German nationalists of Afd, with whom the other parties engaged not to work. "To save democracy you must embrace what people tell you, even if you find it surprising, even if you do not agree," Vance said, addressed to European leaders. The vice president of the United States yesterday gave an interview to the Wall Street Journal in which, while Germany is in full electoral campaign, invited the other German parties to collaborate with the Afd. The statement was strongly criticized by the Berlin government, which assessed it as an interference. The expression used today by Vance, 'firewall', is the translation of the German 'brandmauer', an expression that indicates the "healthy arm" constituted by the rest of German politics around Afd.
<h2>Vance cita Wojtyla, "don't be afraid"</h2>
"Don't be afraid." The Vice-President of the United States, J.D. Vance, concluded his speech at the Munich Security Conference with a quote from John Paul II, "one of the most extraordinary champions of democracy in this continent or any other". "We should not be afraid of our peoples, even when they express views that do not agree with their leadership," said Vance, addressed to European leaders.
